snippet.textDisplay:
HA.

I know it was a joke but... since when was there any rules to how the Force works? In A New Hope, what did the Force do? Give you insight on how to block lasers with a lightsaber while blindfolded? Influence weak minds? Choke people from a distance? That was IT. No more. Oh, and I guess let Luke hear Obi-wan's voice after he was dead. 

Empire Strikes Back: Luke in the Wampa cave... totally high stakes, he is frozen to the ceiling upside down (how does a Wampa even do that to their prey?) and there is no getting out, but wait his lightsaber is there in the snow, but JUUUUUST out of reach. Suddenly, the NEW FORCE POWERS of telekinesis is somehow invented to save our hero from being eaten!

Yeah, what was that about rules of Force powers?? Return of the Jedi: Nobody knows what the fuck the Sith are, hasn't been an invented thing yet, but we know the Emperor has the Force in some capacity... but he can suddenly shoot lightning bolts from his fingers. Okay, now we're just making shit up, STAR WARS!!

Star Wars never set hard rules for The Force. It is an energy field that surrounds us, penetrates us, and binds the universe together. Something that powerful to bind a universe would probably have some pretty cool shit that it can do.

snippet.textDisplay: "When you set up a universe, and create a set of rules, you have to actually follow them." This is my biggest complaint with Star Wars in general, all of the movies, because the rules are never defined. Yes, the lack of definition gets worse in the new movies, but it's been bad everywhere. All that being said, I actually enjoyed The Rise of Skywalker and thought it was fun to watch, even with  all of the problems.
